ownedComment.body: This attribute defines that the target OS has to delete all the interior Group Termination Points (GTPs) supporting the bundled Subnetwork Connection (SNC) when the SNC is deleted. The attribute is only used when creating bundled SNCs. It can take on two possible values: - true (the target OS must make a best-effort attempt to remove the interior GTPs that once belonged to the SNC) and - false (the requesting OS doesn't care if the target OS removes the interior GTPs or not). In the case that mustRemoveGtps is set to "true" and the target OS cannot remove all the interior GTPs, the target OS should return a list of the GTPs that could not be removed in the errorReason field of the deactivateAndDeleteSnc and deleteSnc operations. The errorReason will be "not all interior GTPs could be deleted" - this will be followed by the names of the GTPs that could not be deleted.

This attribute defines if the target OS/Control Plane is allowed and/or required to reroute the Connection if there is a failure on the Connection, periodically to optimize the routes, or for any other reason. It is an target Os/Control Plane implementation whether this is done using network routing protocols or if the target OS/Control Plane detects the failure and takes appropriate action to attempt to fix the Connection.
The NO value means that the target OS/Control Plane is not allowed to reroute the Connection. The YES value means that the target OS/Control Plane is allowed to reroute the Connection and is required to attempt to reroute it upon failure. The NA value is used when the requesting OS does not want to specify the exact target OS/Control Plane behaviour. In this case it is left up to the target OS/Control Plane to decide whether rerouting will be provided. It is also used if the target OS/Control Plane is allowed to reroute the Connection but not required to attempt to reroute it upon failure.
